Date: Tue 27 May 2014
Source: Farmers weekly [edited]
http://www.fwi.co.uk/articles/27/05/2014/144729/russia-battles-fresh-foot-and-mouth-outbreak.htm


Russia battles fresh foot-and-mouth disease outbreak
----------------------------------------------------
More than 10 000 pigs are to be culled after an outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease [FMD] in one of Russia's main pig production regions.

Vets decided to cull all livestock on a farm in [Primorsky krai (Primorye)], in the far east of Russia, after more than 4000 animals showed signs of the disease and more than 2500 died.

Officials said they were culling all the animals because the disease had spread so quickly among livestock since being confirmed last week (21 May 2014). Sergei Sidorenki, the region's vice-governor, said the infected animals were initially going to be treated, but more extreme measures were needed to contain the disease.
"When the virus first hit the complex there were 13 448 pigs of different ages," he said. "More than 2500 animals have died and we are continuing to see new signs of pig mortality. We previously considered a treatment option [see comment], but it increases the possibility that infection could get beyond the farm's territory," he added. [That is why] we decided to destroy all the livestock."

Officials said the farm would be put under quarantine for 3 weeks before being disinfected. The unit could then be restocked after 2 months.

A large-scale vaccination of other livestock in the region will be carried out over the next few days in a bid to contain the disease, they added.

Primorye is one of Russia's most significant pig-producing areas, with plans for a 500 000-head pig production "cluster" unveiled earlier this year [2014]. The USD 1 billion project, which aims to increase pork production by 80 percent, increase exports to Asia, and increase self-sufficiency in the region, includes 6 pig farms, a feed mill, and a genetics centre. The development also includes 7000 ha [1730 acres] of arable land to produce more than 185 000 tons of soya bean and corn for animal feed.

[Byline: Caroline Stocks]

