Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Russia's immediate notification to the OIE on this event was included in ProMED-mail's posting 20140521.2488506.

According to the OIE report, the affected farm included 6780 susceptible pigs, among which there were 4070 "cases"; no mortality or culling were reported.

An OIE report of the previous FMDV serotype O outbreak in Primorye, March 2012, (ProMED-mail posting 20120312.1068385), included the following epidemiological commentary:

"Russian Far East Federal District [Primorsky Krai/Primorye]. Foot and mouth disease virus was detected on a private farm in the village of Usachevka in a remote south-east corner of the country. The outbreak affected 7 cows from 240 cattle heads and 22 small ruminants. The source of the outbreak is currently unknown. The village of Usachevka is located at 45 km [30 mi] from the border between Russia and China. Primorsky krai is part of the buffer zone where cattle and small livestock are vaccinated against foot and mouth disease on an annual basis. All necessary measures to curb the outbreak and prevent the spread of the disease are being taken. According to nucleotide sequencing followed by phylogenetic analysis, the isolate belongs to type O PanAsia genetic lineage and is genetically close to the isolates involved in the FMD outbreaks in China and Eastern Kazakhstan in 2011."

For an updated genotyping report addressing Russian FMDV strains, and a map, please go to page 10 of "WRLFMD Quarterly Report January-March 2014" available at http://www.wrlfmd.org/ref_labs/ref_lab_reports/OIE-FAO%20FMD%20Ref%20Lab%20Report%20Jan-Mar%202014.pdf.

Genotyping results of the current O strain in Primorye are expected.

Subscribers are referred to Mod.CRD's commentary in posting 20140521.2488506. - Mod.AS

Maps of Russia can be seen at http://www.map-of-russia.org/map-of-russia.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2502825,422. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
